LineText: The x86 architecture is a widely used computer processor architecture,
The name comes from the naming of Intel's early processors, such as 8086,
80286, 80386 and 80486, among which "86" became the common identifier of
Backward compatibility: New x86 processors can run software designed for
older processors. This means that code written decades ago can still be run
Widely supported: Due to the popularity of the x86 architecture, almost all
operating systems and software support this architecture. This includes major
operating systems such as Windows, Linux, and macOS.
Extensive hardware and software support: There are a large number of
hardware and software tools designed for the x86 architecture on the market,
ensuring a good ecosystem and user support.
Complex instruction set: x86 is a complex instruction set computer (CISC)
whose instruction set contains a large number of instructions and features
designed to complete complex tasks through a single instruction to reduce
program code length and improve efficiency.
Registers are high-speed storage locations directly inside
Used for arithmetic and data movement
EAX, EBX, ECX, EDX, ESI, EDI, ESP, EBP
Applies to EAX, EBX, Ecx, and EDX
Some registers have only a 16-bit name for their lower half:
Used by multiplication and division instructions
ESP  stack pointer, extended stack pointer register
Used by high-level languages to reference function parameters and local variables
Segment register: as base locations for pre-assigned memory areas
SS (stack segment): Hold local variables and function parameters
Containing the address of the next instruction to be executed
Each flag is a single binary bit
Control the operation of the CPU
Reflect the outcome of some CPU operations, ex:
Auxiliary Carry Flag: carry from bit 3 to bit 4
Parity Flag: sum of 1 bits is an even number
Reserved bit positions- DO NOT USE-
Always set to values previously read-
Only permit access by programs running at the highest privilege level
Control Registers: CRO, CR2, CR3, CR4
Compatibility mode : can run existing 16-bit and 32-bit applications (Windows
supports only 32-bit apps in this mode)
Addresses can be 64 bits (48 bits, in practice)
EAX, EBX, ECX, EDX, EDI, ESI, EBP, ESP, R8D, R9D, RIOD, RIID, R12D, R13D, R14D,
